            <section class="prose mt-10">
              <h2>What is digital accessibility?</h2>
              <p>
                Digital accessibility means designing and developing websites,
                apps, documents and tools so that they can be used by as many
                people as possible, including people with disabilities. This
                includes users who rely on screen readers, keyboard navigation,
                captions, high contrast, voice input, or other assistive
                technologies.
              </p>
              <p>
                The most widely used technical standard is the
                <strong>Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG)</strong>,
                currently at versions 2.1 and 2.2. WCAG defines success criteria
                at three levels:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Level A</strong> – basic accessibility requirements.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Level AA</strong> – widely recommended level for
                  public and commercial sites.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Level AAA</strong> – enhanced accessibility, often not
                  fully achievable for all content.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Why an accessibility statement matters</h3>
              <p>
                An accessibility statement serves several important purposes:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Transparency:</strong> it explains what you are doing
                  to make your service accessible and where there are still
                  barriers.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Trust:</strong> it shows users that you take inclusion
                  seriously and invite feedback.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Compliance:</strong> in many jurisdictions (for
                  example the EU Web Accessibility Directive and the European
                  Accessibility Act) an accessibility statement is required for
                  public sector bodies and certain private services.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Key elements of a strong accessibility statement</h3>
              <p>
                Most reputable guidelines (including W3C WAI and EU models)
                recommend including at least:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Scope:</strong> which website, app or service the
                  statement covers.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Standards:</strong> which accessibility standards and
                  levels you aim to meet (for example WCAG 2.1 AA).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Current status:</strong> whether you are fully,
                  partially or not yet conformant, and how this was assessed
                  (self‑assessment, external audit, automated tools, user
                  testing).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Known limitations:</strong> a list of non‑accessible
                  content or sections, with a short explanation.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Feedback and contact:</strong> how users can report
                  problems or request accessible alternatives.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Enforcement or escalation:</strong> where applicable,
                  information on supervisory bodies or dispute resolution
                  mechanisms.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Review date:</strong> when the statement was last
                  updated.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>European Accessibility Act and other regulations</h3>
              <p>
                In the European Union, the
                <strong>Web Accessibility Directive</strong> and the harmonized
                standard <strong>EN&nbsp;301&nbsp;549</strong> define
                accessibility requirements for public sector websites and apps.
                The <strong>European Accessibility Act (EAA)</strong> extends
                obligations to many private‑sector services (e‑commerce,
                banking, transport, e‑books and more).
              </p>
              <p>
                In the United States, accessibility obligations are mainly
                derived from the
                <strong>Americans with Disabilities Act (ADA)</strong>, Section
                508 of the Rehabilitation Act for federal agencies, and case law
                that increasingly references WCAG as a benchmark.
              </p>
              <p>
                This generator is designed to help you reference these
                frameworks correctly, but it does not check whether your site
                actually complies with them.
              </p>

              <h3>Best practices when using this generator</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Only claim WCAG levels and legal references that you genuinely
                  meet or are actively working towards.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Be honest about known issues and realistic timelines for
                  fixing them.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Test your site with a combination of automated tools, manual
                  checks and, where possible, users with disabilities.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Review and update your accessibility statement at least once a
                  year, or after major redesigns.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>

            <section class="prose mt-10" id="faq">
              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>Do I need a lawyer to write an accessibility statement?</h3>
              <p>
                For most small organizations, a well‑written, honest statement
                based on official models (such as those from W3C WAI or national
                governments) is sufficient. However, if you operate in a highly
                regulated sector or in multiple jurisdictions, legal review can
                be helpful to align your statement with specific obligations.
              </p>

              <h3>Is an accessibility statement enough to be compliant?</h3>
              <p>
                No. A statement is only one part of accessibility compliance.
                Regulators and users will look at the
                <em>actual experience</em> of your website or app. Use this tool
                as a communication aid, not as a substitute for proper design,
                development and testing.
              </p>

              <h3>How can I start improving accessibility on my site?</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>Ensure all images have meaningful alternative text.</li>
                <li>
                  Use sufficient color contrast and avoid relying on color alone
                  to convey information.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Make sure all functionality is available via keyboard, without
                  traps.
                </li>
                <li>Use proper HTML landmarks, headings and labels.</li>
                <li>
                  Provide captions and, where possible, transcripts for audio
                  and video content.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>
